  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Governance in Justice II Programme - Philippines</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">GOJUST II seeks to achieve four major result areas, as follows: 
- Result 1:	 Justice sector coordination mechanisms are improved
- Result 2:	 Strengthened institutional efficiency and effectiveness in the delivery of justice services
- Result 3:	 Increased access to the justice system for vulnerable groups, including women
- Result 4:	 Justice policy and practice is informed by evidence and responds to justice needs


&quot;</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Governance in Justice II (GOJUST II) builds on and continues the work of the predecessor programme, GOJUST I. It contributes to more innovative and streamlined justice reform efforts in pursuit of a common goal of a more efficient, effective, and accountable formal justice system in the Philippines. 
The overall programme is fully funded by the European Union, and implemented by three organisations. British Council manage the technical team and overall technical direction of the programme, with programme management and grants disbursal implemented by UNOPS. A human rights component is implemented by AECID.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Overall objective - to contribute to inclusive and sustainable socio-economic development through improved access to justice for all in the Philippines. 

Specific objective - to develop more responsive and accountable justice services.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&quot;Justice sector officials / duty bearers of the formal justice sector agencies, including 
- the judiciary 
- prosecution service 
- law enforcement agencies 
- correction agencies
- Justice Sector Coordinating Council
- Justice Zones.

Outside the formal justice sector, target groups include
- Civil Society Organisations 
- paralegals
- public interest lawyers
- law students.

Final beneficiaries are rights holders in the form of poor and vulnerable communities including indigenous populations who seek justice services, prisoners on remand, and the broader public.&quot;</narrative>
  </description>
